elements.content: Reductive hydrosilylation of CO2 by catalysts based on environmentally benign metals such as zinc still presents an unmet challenge in terms of catalyst selectivity and activity. Here we show that tetra-coordinated neutral zinc siloxide complexes supported by the β-diketiminato ligand bearing a pendant amine arm exhibit unprecedentedly high catalytic activity toward the selective reduction of CO2 by a hydrosilane to silyl formate. More significantly, this zinc catalyst system can also effectively catalyze the subsequent reduction of silyl formate into methoxysilane in quantitative yield. To understand the mechanism of the CO2 hydrosilylation and the influence of the side arm, a series of catalytic active species (or intermediates), zinc hydrides, and formates, has been synthesized and structurally characterized; the relevant stoichiometric reactions and kinetic study were performed. DFT calculations were also carried out to determine the reaction profiles for the CO2 hydrosilylation and to explain the relative activity of the zinc catalysts employed in this study. This combined experimental and theoretical study gives insights into the critical effects of the pendant amine donor arm and the size of the alkyl group of the amine on the relative energetics of the species involved in the proposed catalytic cycle.

elements.content: The use of carbon dioxide (CO2) as a renewable feedstock for the synthesis of valuable chemicals received increasing attention in the last deacade. Hydrosilylation of CO2 to silyl formate, bis­(silylacetal), methoxysilane, or methane is a thermodynamically favorable process for CO2 transformation due to the formation of strong Si–O bonds, and the generated silyl formate, bis­(silylacetal), and methoxysilane can be readily converted into formic acid, formamides, formaldehyde, or methanol. Therefore, many homogeneous transition-metal catalysts (Ru, Ir, Rh, Co, Ni, Cu, Pd/Pt, Sc, and Zr), frustrated Lewis pairs (FLPs) as well as organocatalysts and main-group Lewis acid catalysts have been explored for this important transformation.
elements.clean_text:
Introduction

The use of carbon dioxide (CO2) as a renewable feedstock for the synthesis of valuable chemicals received increasing attention in the last deacade. Hydrosilylation of CO2 to silyl formate, bis(silylacetal), methoxysilane, or methane is a thermodynamically favorable process for CO2 transformation due to the formation of strong Si-O bonds, and the generated silyl formate, bis(silylacetal), and methoxysilane can be readily converted into formic acid, formamides, formaldehyde, or methanol. Therefore, many homogeneous transition-metal catalysts (Ru, Ir, Rh, Co, Ni, Cu, Pd/Pt, Sc, and Zr), frustrated Lewis pairs (FLPs) as well as organocatalysts and main-group Lewis acid catalysts have been explored for this important transformation.

elements.content: As an abundant, biocompatible, and environmentally friendly metal ion, zinc-based complexes have been utilized in many interesting and important stoichiometric and catalytic reactions. Although ZnR2 (R = alkyl) species have been widely used as reducing or transmetalation agents in hydrocarboxylation of unsaturated hydrocarbons with CO2 and (β-diketiminato)zinc complexes are some of the best catalysts for copolymerization of CO2 with epoxides, the utilization of homogeneous zinc complexes as catalysts or precatalysts for CO2 reduction achieved no significant advances until recently. The groups of Wehmschulte, Parkin, Okuda, and Dagorne found that zinc complexes are capable of catalyzing CO2 hydrosilylation to produce methane, silyl formate, bis­(silylacetal), or methoxysilane. Likewise, Cantat’s group reported the zinc-catalyzed methylation of N–H bonds using CO2 and hydrosilanes. Nevertheless, the examples of the zinc-catalyzed CO2 hydrosilylation remain scarce, and the catalytic activity is relatively low. The reported zinc catalysts are mostly in the form of precious ion-pairs, such as [ZnEt]­[CHB11Cl11], [(NHC)­ZnMe]­[B­(C6F5)4], {[Tism iPrBenz]­Zn}­[HB­(C6F5)3], [(NHC)3Zn3H4(THF)]­[BPh4]2, and [(nNHC)­(aNHC)­ZnMe]­[B­(C6F5)4]. Hence, it would be more desirable to develop a neutral zinc catalyst system that exhibits high activity and selectivity for this transformation. To this end, we exploited β-diketiminato ligands bearing a pendant amine donor, the ligand system that delivered unique stabilization for highly reactive rare-earth metal complexes, to support neutral zinc triphenylsiloxide complexes. The resulting complexes exhibit remarkably high activity in catalyzing CO2 hydrosilylation to silyl formate selectively and, more significantly, they also efficiently catalyze the further reduction of the generated silyl formate to methoxysilane. Furthermore, the pendant amine arm of the supporting ligand was found to substantially affect the catalytic activity of the complex. A combined experimental and DFT study provided critical insights into the mechanism of this neutral zinc-catalyzed CO2 hydrosilylation and the influence of the side arm.

elements.content: Zinc triphenylsiloxides 1–4 () were synthesized from reactions of the corresponding zinc ethyl or amido complexes with Ph3SiOH in 75–99% yields (see the , SI). Zinc triphenylsiloxide 5 supported by the conventional bidentate β-diketiminato ligand was also synthesized. All these complexes were characterized by NMR spectroscopy and elemental analysis, and the structure of 1 was further characterized by single crystal X-ray diffraction. In 1, the zinc center is coordinated by three nitrogen atoms of the tridentate ligand and one oxygen atom of the OSiPh3 group, displaying a distorted tetrahedral geometry (). As expected, the Zn–N3 (pendant arm) bond length [2.138(2) Å] is significantly longer than the Zn–N1 and Zn–N2 bond lengths [1.980(1) and 1.989(2) Å], because the pendant arm acts as a neutral donor while the backbone is an anionic donor. The Zn–O bond length is 1.895(1) Å, and the Zn–O–Si bond angle is 136.0(1)o.
elements.clean_text:
Results and Discussion

Synthesis and Structural Characterization of Zinc Triphenylsiloxides

Zinc triphenylsiloxides 1-4 () were synthesized from reactions of the corresponding zinc ethyl or amido complexes with Ph3SiOH in 75-99% yields (see the , SI). Zinc triphenylsiloxide 5 supported by the conventional bidentate β-diketiminato ligand was also synthesized. All these complexes were characterized by NMR spectroscopy and elemental analysis, and the structure of 1 was further characterized by single crystal X-ray diffraction. In 1, the zinc center is coordinated by three nitrogen atoms of the tridentate ligand and one oxygen atom of the OSiPh3 group, displaying a distorted tetrahedral geometry (). As expected, the Zn-N3 (pendant arm) bond length [2.138(2) Å] is significantly longer than the Zn-N1 and Zn-N2 bond lengths [1.980(1) and 1.989(2) Å], because the pendant arm acts as a neutral donor while the backbone is an anionic donor. The Zn-O bond length is 1.895(1) Å, and the Zn-O-Si bond angle is 136.0(1)o.

elements.content: Complex 1 (0.125 mol %) was initially tested for catalytic hydrosilylation of CO2 with inexpensive, commercially available (EtO)3SiH as the reducing agent, and reactions were carried out under neat conditions for 5 h with an initial CO2 pressure of 140 psi. Selective reduction of CO2 to HCO2Si­(OEt)3 was observed (); no further reduced products, CH2(OSi­(OEt)3)2 and CH3OSi­(OEt)3, were detected from the 1H NMR spectra. The yields of HCO2Si­(OEt)3 were slightly lower than the conversions of (EtO)3SiH, due to the disproportionation of (EtO)3SiH into SiH4 and Si­(OEt)4 under the reaction conditions. When the reaction temperature was increased from 70 to 90 °C, the yield of HCO2Si­(OEt)3 increased accordingly (entries 1–3). A further increase in the temperature to 100 °C did not give additional change in the yield (entry 4). Increasing the CO2 pressure from 140 to 200 and 260 psi resulted in only marginal improvement over the product yield (entries 5 and 6 vs entry 3). The catalytic properties of 2-5 for the CO2 hydrosilylation were subsequently studied. Overall, the catalytic activity of 3 is similar to that of 1, but those of 2 and 4 are significantly lower under the same reaction conditions. Complex 5 that bears the bidentate ligand only produced a small amount of HCO2Si­(OEt)3. When the loading of 1 decreased to 0.0625 mol % (entry 12), 78% yield of HCO2Si­(OEt)3 was achieved after 40 h, which gave a turnover number (TON) of 1242 and a turnover frequency (TOF) of 31 h–1. Thus, the catalytic activity of 1 is about 10 times higher than that of Parkin’s complex [κ3-Tptm]­ZnH (TON = 1000, TOF = 2.9 h–1) under similar reaction conditions, representing the most active zinc catalyst for the CO2 hydrosilylation to HCO2Si­(OEt)3 to date.

Hydrosilylation of CO2 to HCO2Si(OEt)3 

Complex 1 (0.125 mol %) was initially tested for catalytic hydrosilylation of CO2 with inexpensive, commercially available (EtO)3SiH as the reducing agent, and reactions were carried out under neat conditions for 5 h with an initial CO2 pressure of 140 psi. Selective reduction of CO2 to HCO2Si(OEt)3 was observed (); no further reduced products, CH2(OSi(OEt)3)2 and CH3OSi(OEt)3, were detected from the 1H NMR spectra. The yields of HCO2Si(OEt)3 were slightly lower than the conversions of (EtO)3SiH, due to the disproportionation of (EtO)3SiH into SiH4 and Si(OEt)4 under the reaction conditions. When the reaction temperature was increased from 70 to 90 °C, the yield of HCO2Si(OEt)3 increased accordingly (entries 1-3). A further increase in the temperature to 100 °C did not give additional change in the yield (entry 4). Increasing the CO2 pressure from 140 to 200 and 260 psi resulted in only marginal improvement over the product yield (entries 5 and 6 vs entry 3). The catalytic properties of 2-5 for the CO2 hydrosilylation were subsequently studied. Overall, the catalytic activity of 3 is similar to that of 1, but those of 2 and 4 are significantly lower under the same reaction conditions. Complex 5 that bears the bidentate ligand only produced a small amount of HCO2Si(OEt)3. When the loading of 1 decreased to 0.0625 mol % (entry 12), 78% yield of HCO2Si(OEt)3 was achieved after 40 h, which gave a turnover number (TON) of 1242 and a turnover frequency (TOF) of 31 h-1. Thus, the catalytic activity of 1 is about 10 times higher than that of Parkin's complex [κ3-Tptm]ZnH (TON = 1000, TOF = 2.9 h-1) under similar reaction conditions, representing the most active zinc catalyst for the CO2 hydrosilylation to HCO2Si(OEt)3 to date.

The conversion of (EtO)3SiH and the yields of HCO2Si­(OEt)3 and Si­(OEt)4 were determined by quantitative 13C NMR, as there was a disproportionation of (EtO)3SiH into SiH4 and Si­(OEt)4 under the reaction conditions.

TON and TOF values were calculated based on the amount of HCO2Si­(OEt)3 produced.

Reaction time was 40 h.

To understand the mechanism of the catalytic reaction described above and the influence of the side arm, several relevant stoichiometric reactions were performed. First, monitoring of the reactions of zinc triphenylsiloxides 1, 2, and 5 with 5 equiv of (EtO)3SiH by 1H NMR in C6D6 clearly showed a complete conversion of the zinc triphenylsiloxides into the corresponding zinc hydrides L1ZnH, [L2ZnH]2, and L5ZnH in 20, 20, and 50 min, respectively, at room temperature (, Figures S38–S40 in the ). Scaled-up reactions in toluene provided [L2ZnH]2 and L5ZnH in nearly quantitative yields, while the isolation of L1ZnH was hampered by its high solubility in toluene or hexane. Thus, L1ZnH was alternatively synthesized in high yield via the reaction of L1ZnOEt with (EtO)3SiH.

elements.content: Both L1ZnH and [L2ZnH]2 were characterized by NMR spectroscopy, elemental analysis, and single crystal X-ray diffraction (), while L5ZnH is a known complex. L1ZnH was crystallographically characterized as a monomer with the ligand L1 κ3-N,N,N-chelating to the metal center. The Zn–H distance (1.59(2) Å) is much longer than that in L5ZnH (1.46(2) Å), due to an increase in coordination number from 3 in L5ZnH to 4 in L1ZnH. In contrast to L1ZnH and L5ZnH, [L2ZnH]2 crystallizes as a dimer with two bridging hydrido ligands, and the amino side arm of the tridentate ligand (L2) is not coordinated to the zinc center. The Zn–H distances of 1.693(15) and 1.710(18) Å are much longer than those in L1ZnH and L5ZnH, but slightly shorter than that in the dimer [(Mes-nacnac)­ZnH]2 (Mes-nacnac = [CH­{MeC­(NC6H3-2,6-Me2)}2]−) (1.766 Å). The structural differences between L1ZnH and [L2ZnH]2 are apparently due to the weaker coordination ability of the N i Pr2 group compared to the NMe2 group. The solution behavior of L1ZnH, [L2ZnH]2, and L5ZnH were also studied. 1H NMR DOSY measurements of the toluene-d 8 solutions at 25 °C showed that the hydrodynamic radii of L1ZnH, [L2ZnH]2, and L5ZnH are 4.77, 5.35, and 5.32 Å, respectively. Therefore, all these three zinc hydrides are monomeric in solution, although [L2ZnH]2 exists as a dimer in the solid state.

elements.content: Zinc hydrides L1ZnH, [L2ZnH]2, and L5ZnH were readily converted into zinc formates L1ZnO2CH, [L2ZnO2CH]2, and [L5ZnO2CH]2 (or L5ZnO2CH) in 15 min, 1 h, and 1 h, respectively, upon the addition of CO2 (1.0 atm) at room temperature (, Figures S53–55 in the ). All of these three zinc formates were isolated and characterized by NMR spectroscopy, elemental analysis, and single crystal X-ray diffraction (a, b). L1ZnO2CH has a polymeric structure in the solid state. Each zinc ion is coordinated by three nitrogen atoms of L1 and one oxygen atom from each of the two formate groups with the formate group bridging the two zinc ions through two oxygen atoms. [L2ZnO2CH]2 exists as an unsymmetric dimer, with the two zinc ions being linked by the two formate groups, where one formate group adopts a bridging bidentate coordination mode while the other serves as a bridging monodentate ligand. Similar to what was observed for [L2ZnH]2, the amino side arm of L2 in [L2ZnO2CH]2 remains uncoordinated. [L5ZnO2CH]2 is a symmetric dimer with each formate group bridging two zinc centers through two oxygen atoms. 1H NMR DOSY experiments in toluene-d 8 at 25 °C suggested L1ZnO2CH exists as a monomer while [L2ZnO2CH]2 is largely dimeric in solution, and their hydrodynamic radii are 4.95 and 6.88 Å, respectively. Interestingly, the 1H NMR spectra of [L5ZnO2CH]2 clearly showed two sets of signals for two isomers in solution, one is a dimer with a hydrodynamic radius of 6.88 Å and the other is a monomer with a hydrodynamic radius of 5.36 Å. The 1H NMR spectroscopy investigation of the C6D6 solutions at different [L5ZnO2CH]2 concentrations provided an equilibrium constant of 8.0 × 10–3 mol/L at 25 °C according to the equation K e = [monomer]2/[dimer]. The 1H NMR spectroscopy monitoring also revealed that the conversion of the monomer into the dimer is relatively slow at room temperature (Figure S57 in the )

elements.content: During the 1H NMR spectral monitoring of the reaction of [L2ZnH]2 with CO2 in C6D6, an intermediate was observed. The 1H NMR spectrum of this intermediate displayed two signals at 8.55 and 3.78 ppm, which are typical for ZnO2CH and ZnH, respectively. Therefore, we supposed it is an adduct of L2ZnH and L2ZnO2CH. To confirm the structure of this intermediate, an equimolar reaction of [L2ZnH]2 and [L2ZnO2CH]2 in hexane was carried out, which provided the intermediate in a quantitatively yield (). The complex was characterized by NMR spectroscopy, elemental analysis, and single crystal X-ray diffraction, confirming that it is L2Zn­(O2CH)­(H)­ZnL2 (). In L2Zn­(O2CH)­(H)­ZnL2, two zinc ions are both bridged by one formate group and one hydrido ligand. The Zn–H distances (1.66(2) and 1.70(2) Å) are close to those in [L2ZnH]2 (1.69(2) and 1.71(2) Å) and the Zn–O distances (2.026(2) and 1.995(2) Å) are similar to those in [L2ZnO2CH]2 (1.999(1) and 2.002(1) Å). The formation of L2Zn­(O2CH)­(H)­ZnL2 from [L2ZnH]2 and [L2ZnO2CH]2 indicated that L2Zn­(O2CH)­(H)­ZnL2 could be a resting state in the CO2 hydrosilylation catalyzed by complex 2. 1H NMR DOSY measurements in toluene-d 8 of L2Zn­(O2CH)­(H)­ZnL2 at 25 °C provided a hydrodynamic radius value of 6.07 Å, revealing a monomer–dimer equilibrium in the solution.

elements.content: 1H NMR spectroscopy monitoring of the reactions of (EtO)3SiH with the formates, L1ZnO2CH, [L2ZnO2CH]2, or [L5ZnO2CH]2, in C6D6 at 70 °C clearly showed the regeneration of the zinc hydrides, L1ZnH, [L2ZnH]2, or L5ZnH. Next, the associated kinetic studies were performed. The reactions of L1ZnO2CH with 20 equiv of (EtO)3SiH in C6D6 at six different temperatures between 54 and 74 °C all fit with a first order in L1ZnO2CH (see the ), and the first-order plot with respect to L1ZnO2CH at 70.0 °C is shown in . An Eyring analysis provided activation parameters of ΔH ‡ = 13.6(6) kcal/mol, ΔS ‡ = −35(2) cal/mol·K, and ΔG ‡ = 24.0 kcal/mol for 298.2 K (). The large negative entropy of activation is consistent with an associative mechanism. The reactions of (EtO)3SiH with [L2ZnO2CH]2 or [L5ZnO2CH]2 were complicated and did not follow the first-order kinetics. These observations are in line with the complexity of [L2ZnO2CH]2 or [L5ZnO2CH]2 in solution as discussed above, such as formation of L2Zn­(O2CH)­(H)­ZnL2 with the regenerated [L2ZnH]2 or the slow equilibrium between the monomer L5ZnO2CH and the dimer [L5ZnO2CH]2. Although the detailed kinetic information on the reactions of (EtO)3SiH with [L2ZnO2CH]2 or [L5ZnO2CH]2 was not obtained, 1H NMR spectroscopy monitoring of the reactions of L1ZnO2CH, [L2ZnO2CH]2, or [L5ZnO2CH]2 with 20 equiv of (EtO)3SiH in C6D6 at 70 °C clearly showed that the reaction times for a 70% conversion of the formates were 50, 30, and 5 min (Figures S58–S60 in the ), respectively. The catalytic behavior of complex 5 apparently did not fit the studied three stoichiometric reactions. CO2 was added to the reaction mixture after complex 5 and 800 equiv of (EtO)3SiH were mixed for 30 min, after which complex 5 was completely converted into the hydride before the addition of CO2. According to the stoichiometric studies, the catalytic activity of complex 5 should be higher than that of complex 1. Speculating that the observed low catalytic activity of complex 5 could be due to fast decomposition of the catalytic species, we then reinvestigated the CO2 hydrosilylation catalyzed by complex 5 (0.125 mol %) at 70 °C with an initial CO2 pressure of 140 psi. Rather similar conversions of (EtO)3SiH (5–6%) were observed for the reactions at three different reaction times (1, 3, and 5 h), thus revealing that the low catalytic activity of complex 5 is indeed due to fast decomposition of the catalytic species under catalytic conditions.

elements.content: To gain insights into the reactivity of complex 1, possible reaction pathway () was determined through DFT studies (B3PW91 level, see the ). The reaction begins with the formation of the hydride complex through a σ-bond metathesis. This step appears to be kinetically more facile for 1 and 3 than 2 (Figure S65 in the ). Then, the CO2 insertion proceeds with a readily accessible energy barrier (22.8 kcal/mol), more or less the same for the three catalysts. The insertion step leads to a η1-formate that rapidly transforms into the more stable η2-formate, the latter of which needs to undergo a rotation to react further. This step is the most critical one as it is endergonic by 6.4 kcal/mol for 1 (10.5 kcal/mol for 2 and 7.2 kcal/mol for 3) and occurs prior to the regeneration of the hydride, for which the barrier is in the same order as for the first hydride formation (this holds true also for complexes 2 and 3). Interestingly enough, the hydride regeneration step was also found to be endergonic for the Parkin’s catalyst by 9.9 kcal/mol (Figure S66 in the ). The Gibbs Free Energy computed barrier from the η2-formate complex is 31.3 kcal/mol, in good agreement with the experimental value of 24.0 kcal/mol, keeping in mind the well-known error associated with the entropy determination computationally. Interestingly, the pendant arm is found to decoordinate for 2 to allow the reaction, whereas it is not the case for 1 and 3. Therefore, the effect of the presence of the pendant arm was investigated in more details as the reaction involves 5-coordinated species for complex 1 and 3 but only 4-coordinated ones for complex 2. Removing the coordination of the pendant arm in complex 1 leads to an overall similar reactivity to that with the arm coordinated (Figure S67 in the ). Therefore, the decoordination of the amine arm in complex 2 is a steric effect rather than an electronic one as the reactivity of the 5-coordinated zinc is similar to that of the 4-coordinated species. However, the formation of the complex 1-H from complex 1 appears to be more favorable in the absence of extra-coordination. This fits with an electronic effect and especially with the presence of 4 valence orbitals in Zn. This easiest hydride formation is reminiscent of what was also observed experimentally for complex 5, where no pendant arm is present, and was thus investigated computationally. Interestingly, the computed profile for complex 5 (Figure S68) is similar to that found for complex 1′ (complex 1 without the pendant arm coordinated, see the ). Therefore, one can conclude that the pendant arm’s coordination is crucial to increase the stability of the catalyst by decreasing its decomposition. Effect of solvent and dispersion were evaluated (Figure S69) and appears to strongly reduce the first barrier (hydride formation from the precatalyst).

elements.content: In the reaction of zinc formate L1ZnO2CH with (EtO)3SiH, a further reduced product CH3OSi­(OEt)3 was observed, which prompted us to study the reduction of HCO2Si­(OEt)3 with hydrosilane catalyzed by zinc complexes (). Reactions were also carried out under neat conditions, and due to the disproportionation of HSi­(OEt)3, 3 equiv (EtO)3SiH rather than 2 equiv (EtO)3SiH was used. No reaction occurred between HCO2Si­(OEt)3 and (EtO)3SiH at 70 °C in the absence of catalyst, while the addition of complex 1 clearly promoted the reaction to afford CH3OSi­(OEt)3 selectively. HCO2Si­(OEt)3 was quantitatively converted into CH3OSi­(OEt)3 with 2 or 1 mol % of complex 1 within 12 or 24 h at 70 °C (entries 2 and 3). The catalytic activity of complex 3 is about 1/3 lower than that of 1 under the same reaction conditions (entry 3 vs 5). PhSiH3 and Et3SiH were also employed as the reductants; PhSiH3 gave 98% yield with 2 mol % of complex 1 within 12 h while no products were observed when Et3SiH was used (entries 6 and 7). Some other zinc complexes were also tested for the hydrosilylation of HCO2Si­(OEt)3 with (EtO)3SiH. ZnCl2 and (IPr)­ZnCl2 (IPr = 1,3-bis­(2,6-diisopropylphenyl)­imidazol-2-ylidene) catalyzed the reaction and selectively produced CH3OSi­(OEt)3 in low yields (10–37%), while Zn­(OAc)2 and Zn­[N­(SiMe3)2]2 did not produce any CH3OSi­(OEt)3 (entries 8–11).

Hydrosilylation of HCO2Si(OEt)3 to CH3OSi(OEt)3 

In the reaction of zinc formate L1ZnO2CH with (EtO)3SiH, a further reduced product CH3OSi(OEt)3 was observed, which prompted us to study the reduction of HCO2Si(OEt)3 with hydrosilane catalyzed by zinc complexes (). Reactions were also carried out under neat conditions, and due to the disproportionation of HSi(OEt)3, 3 equiv (EtO)3SiH rather than 2 equiv (EtO)3SiH was used. No reaction occurred between HCO2Si(OEt)3 and (EtO)3SiH at 70 °C in the absence of catalyst, while the addition of complex 1 clearly promoted the reaction to afford CH3OSi(OEt)3 selectively. HCO2Si(OEt)3 was quantitatively converted into CH3OSi(OEt)3 with 2 or 1 mol % of complex 1 within 12 or 24 h at 70 °C (entries 2 and 3). The catalytic activity of complex 3 is about 1/3 lower than that of 1 under the same reaction conditions (entry 3 vs 5). PhSiH3 and Et3SiH were also employed as the reductants; PhSiH3 gave 98% yield with 2 mol % of complex 1 within 12 h while no products were observed when Et3SiH was used (entries 6 and 7). Some other zinc complexes were also tested for the hydrosilylation of HCO2Si(OEt)3 with (EtO)3SiH. ZnCl2 and (IPr)ZnCl2 (IPr = 1,3-bis(2,6-diisopropylphenyl)imidazol-2-ylidene) catalyzed the reaction and selectively produced CH3OSi(OEt)3 in low yields (10-37%), while Zn(OAc)2 and Zn[N(SiMe3)2]2 did not produce any CH3OSi(OEt)3 (entries 8-11).

elements.content: In summary, in sharp contrast to the zinc siloxide supported by the conventional bidentate β-diketiminato ligand, which showed marginal catalytic activity toward hydrosilylative reduction of CO2 to silyl formate, zinc siloxides supported by the β-diketiminato ligand bearing a pendant amine donor exhibits high catalytic activity for the selective reduction reaction. This corresponds to a roughly 10-fold rate enhancement over the best zinc catalyst ([κ3-Tptm]­ZnH) reported to date. More significantly, the current new zinc catalyst system can also effectively catalyze the further reduction of the resulting silyl formate into methoxysilane in quantitative yield. A combined experimental (through isolation and structural characterization of active intermediates, stoichiometric reactions, and kinetic study) and theoretical (through DFT determination of reaction profiles) study of the hydrosilylation of CO2 to silyl formate revealed key fundamental steps involved in the catalytic cycle, including formation of catalyst (Zn–H species), CO2 insertion, formate isomerization/reorganization, and catalyst regeneration. The study also demonstrated that the side arm’s coordination is crucial to increase the stability of the zinc hydride catalyst by decreasing the speed of the hydride formation that can decompose fast. This result should inspire further development of zinc-catalyzed transformations where the zinc hydride is involved.
elements.clean_text:
Conclusions

In summary, in sharp contrast to the zinc siloxide supported by the conventional bidentate β-diketiminato ligand, which showed marginal catalytic activity toward hydrosilylative reduction of CO2 to silyl formate, zinc siloxides supported by the β-diketiminato ligand bearing a pendant amine donor exhibits high catalytic activity for the selective reduction reaction. This corresponds to a roughly 10-fold rate enhancement over the best zinc catalyst ([κ3-Tptm]ZnH) reported to date. More significantly, the current new zinc catalyst system can also effectively catalyze the further reduction of the resulting silyl formate into methoxysilane in quantitative yield. A combined experimental (through isolation and structural characterization of active intermediates, stoichiometric reactions, and kinetic study) and theoretical (through DFT determination of reaction profiles) study of the hydrosilylation of CO2 to silyl formate revealed key fundamental steps involved in the catalytic cycle, including formation of catalyst (Zn-H species), CO2 insertion, formate isomerization/reorganization, and catalyst regeneration. The study also demonstrated that the side arm's coordination is crucial to increase the stability of the zinc hydride catalyst by decreasing the speed of the hydride formation that can decompose fast. This result should inspire further development of zinc-catalyzed transformations where the zinc hydride is involved.
